omy of the Passions is how techniques of studying facial musculature became a point of contact between existing and novel understandings of the body's expressive anatomy. Delaporte shows that Duchenne entirely reordered the knowledge and limits of expressive physiology in science and art. The face became a site where the signs of inner life are silently revealed, not yet betrayed by speech, but brought forth by reflexive physiology or by technical manipulation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aHistory -- Intellectual and Cultural. 4aHistory -- Science, Technology, and Medicine. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh1 aMeyers, Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyers, Todd, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362706240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503627062423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503627062/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles